('101','Picacho Peak','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Two-Cars','4.70','1200','Moderate','None','Views','All','Full sun','Picacho_Peak.GPX','Picacho_Peak.json','35.6860397000','-105.8957781000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157674844266790','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157672400139854','https://www.google.com/maps/dir/35.6860397,-105.8957781/Atalaya - Upper Trailhead (recgovnpsdata), Santa Fe, NM 87505/@35.6771424,-105.9129916,14.69z/data=!4m9!4m8!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8718510b3b76eee9:0x46aed0d056701831!2m2!1d-105.9005356!2d35.6700591!3e0','The Picacho Peak Trail is actually a part of the Dale Ball Trail System of Santa Fe. Being close to Santa Fe makes the hike accessible   to locals. That means parking can be a problem, especially at the Atalaya Upper Trailhead (off Camino de Cruz Blanca) where space is   quite limited.','The authors did this as a one-way (two-car) hike starting at the Atalaya Upper Trailhead and ending at the Canyon Road trailhead. On   the way down towards Canyon Road, they made a detour off the main trail that is flagged on the Actual Hike map.  This hike can also be done as an \"out-and-back\" hike from either of the two trailheads, the distance to the top being roughly equal   regardless of the starting point.  <br />  There are numerous nice views of the Santa Fe valley as you go. From the summit of Picacho, the view extends north along the Sangre de   Cristos, southeast to Atalaya Ridge, south to Sun and Moon Mountains, and southwest to the Sandia. The trail is well-defined and   ascends at a reasonable rate, a bit steeper near the summit. '),
('102','Dragon\'s Back','mstr','San Ysidro','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','5.90','350','Moderate','None','Panoramic Views','Not Summer','Full sun','White_Mesa_BT.GPX','White_Mesa_BT.json','35.4984000000','-106.8414000000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157676308235354','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157678091862331','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//White Mesa Bike Trails, 4493 Cabezon Rd, Rio Rancho, NM 87124/@35.4944866,-106.8468055,15.59z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x87228b8ba777132f:0x210ac2b8313d0ff7!2sWhite Mesa Bike Trails!8m2!3d35.4984664!4d-106.8414231!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x87228b8ba777132f:0x210ac2b8313d0ff7!2m2!1d-106.8414231!2d35.4984664','The Bike Trails are actually suitable for biking, hiking, and equestrian activity, depending on the difficulty chosen. Each trail segment is indicated by a number - but unfortunately, many of the signs indicating the trail segment are now missing. The authors mistakenly took the Dragon\'s Back Trail, but were more than happy with the scenery it provided. When attempting to re-connect with the intended hike, some precarious trails were taken, first descending into the valley, and then scaling it part-way up on narrow, steep paths along the way, which were actually dangerous. It is highly recommended that you carefully plan your route prior to embarking on it.','The ample gravel parking lot off of Cabezon Road provides access to the trailhead. It is well-marked and easy to find. What is not easy is finding the desired trail segments (see Trail Tips, above). This hike ended up traversing part of the Dragon\'s back, which provided fantastic panoramic views of the area - from the Jemez Mountains and part of the Sangre de Cristos, to Cabezon Peak, and parts of the Ojito Wilderness area. The authors descended into the colorful valley for part of the trip which led to other great views. Plan the route carefully, and pay special attention to forks which may be un-marked. The area is well worth a visit!'),
('103','Chino Mesa','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'J','Chino Mesa Group','Loop','2.30','500','Easy-Moderate','None','Canyon Views','Not Summer','Full sun','Chino_Mesa.GPX','Chino_Mesa.json','35.7572026200','-106.2020749000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157675319923312','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157672782689506','https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B045\'26.0%22N+106%C2%B012\'08.0%22W/@35.752084,-106.2023449,13z','As with other hikes on Chino Mesa, access is via FR24 - a poorly maintained dirt road, with rocks, close-in junipers and cactus, and other hazards. A high-clearance, 4-wheel drive vehicle is a must. As with the Pinabete Tank hike, take NM62 off of Caja Del Rio Road, and watch for a fork. Take the right branch. This hike however branches off to the left before Pinabete Tank, and stopped near a powerline road, which became to difficult to traverse by vehicle. Good maps of the area are highly recommended.','This hike follows the powerline road down towards the rim of the canyon. At some point the authors descended in an attempt to find\na way down to the Rio Grande. Although unsuccessful, the views were well worth the trip. As with Pinabete Tank, there are no\nreferences for this hike, and there are no trails.'),
('104','Twin Hills','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'J','Chino Mesa Group','Loop','6.60','800','Moderate','None','Volcanic Features','Not Summer','Full sun','TwinHills.GPX','TwinHills.json','35.7041578300','-106.1193397000','a:3:{i:0;s:14:\"MontosoKey.jpg\";i:1;s:3:\"260\";i:2;s:3:\"421\";}','a:3:{i:0;s:17:\"MontosoPkArea.jpg\";i:1;s:3:\"260\";i:2;s:3:\"332\";}','https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157674263303274','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157677808580075','https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B042\'15.4%22N+106%C2%B007\'26.8%22W/@35.6938831,-106.119556,13z','This hike in the Chino Mesa area is also accessed via the unmaintained FR24 off of NM62. Travel on FR24 requires a high-clearance 4-wheel drive vehicle, and some areas are boxed in by juniper and cactus, or traverse very rocky patches. The tracks are deeply rutted and require careful navigation. This hike begins far earlier on FR24 than Chino Mesa or Pinabete Tank, but the branch off of FR24 can also be traveled a distance, to be determined by the driver.','There are no trails in this area, though the early part of the hike can follow the double-track \"road\" towards the hills. There is also a verbal description in the book reference listed below, but the authors had some trouble mapping the description to the actual hike. Hence, this hike, in part, was an experience in bush-whacking and was often based on curiosity about some of the volcanic features: cones, plugs, and vents. Throughout the hike, the views of the volcanic plateau are extensive and interesting. There has been a significant geological study of the area - Montoso Peak - for which a link has been provided in the references. Since the travel on FR24 is significantly less than the Chino Mesa or Pinabete Tank hikes, it can provide an accessible an interesting hike and an adventure limited only by your desire to explore.'),
('105','Piedra Lisa','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'K','Piedra Lisa Group','Two-Cars','4.80','1300','Easy-Moderate','None','Rincon Ridge','Any','Mixed sun/shade','Piedra_Lisa.GPX','Piedra_Lisa.json','35.2228239400','-106.4834739000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157678405221071','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157680212704305','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Piedra Lisa-south Trailhead/@35.2211432,-106.4879391,15.8z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87189c33b662307d:0x92c0ead8cf18c3c4!8m2!3d35.2231347!4d-106.4834646',NULL,'The Piedra Lisa Trail, located on FR333 off of Tramway Blvd, just past the Juan Tabo Picnic area and La Luz Trailhead, is nestled in the Rincon Valley. There are other areas in Albuquerque also called Piedra Lisa, and this one is marked \"Piedra Lisa-south\" for reasons unknown. From the ample parking area, there are pleasant and scenic views of the Sandias and also Rincon Ridge, which\nsits immediately west of the Sandia. The Piedra Lisa trail is well marked and from the parking lot, parallels FR333 a short while before dropping into a trail juncture of Piedra Lisa, Waterfall Canyon, Fletcher Trail, and Movie Trail. Piedra Lisa continues left of these other trailheads and essentially straight across the arroyo there. From here the trail goes up, non-stop, to the top of Rincon Ridge, with great views of both the Sandia and Rincon Ridge along the way. The trail continues past the ridge top towards\nPlacitas for those who wish to go further, but the authors returned to the starting point from the top. '),
('106','Cerro Columbo','mstr','Golden','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Two-Cars','4.30','750','Easy-Moderate','None','San Pedro Views','Any','Full sun','Cerro_Columbo.GPX','Cerro_Columbo.json','35.2393994000','-106.2111358000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157677002745174','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157680577851875','https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B014\'21.8%22N+106%C2%B012\'40.1%22W/@35.2406886,-106.2184074,14z','The access to the hike, although owned by BLM, has what appears to be a locked gate. In actuality, at the time of this visit, the chain on the gate was simply hooked and easily undone to allow access beyond. The distance from the road to the hike start point is rather small, so it is not required to park beyond the gate if locked.<p>The San Pedros were a part of the old Gold Rush and hence have many abandoned mines throughout. These are generally not closed off, so do not attempt to enter them.</p>','The San Pedros are a smaller range northeast of Albuquerque, but provide some unique vistas of the surrounding terrain - from the back of the Sandia (Eastern slopes) to the Ortiz, and beyond. From the entrance gate, there are multiple double-track jeep trails proceeding in various directions. This hike attempted to follow a route provided in the references to the top of Cerro Columbo. At the beginning of the hike, prior to the diverging trails, is a large and interesting field of obsidian which appears to have been partially disrupted by mining or other efforts. The jeep trails wander throughout the area, so the authors did some off-trail exploring to gain access to the top of Cerro Columbo. From the top, other parts of the San Pedros are visible: South Mountain, Lone Mountain, and other unnamed peaks. The trail begins off of NM344 not far from NM14 near Golden.'),
('107','Diablo Mesa','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'L','Diablo Canyon Group','Loop','2.70','500','Moderate','None','Diablo Canyon Views','Not Summer','Full sun','DiabloMesa.GPX','DiabloMesa.json','35.8045013600','-106.1360877000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157677124673434','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157680655735325','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Diablo Canyon Recreation Area/@35.8105225,-106.1646954,14.43z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x871841cc309ae52d:0x694906cba94e2b69!8m2!3d35.806363!4d-106.142693',NULL,'There is a trail from the Parking Lot / Camping Area that proceeds up to the top of Diablo Canyon, which the authors failed to discover until later on (see hike map). The trail is slightly steep as it ascends, and there are no trails on top. The top of Diablo Canyon is not really a (flat) mesa, as it has many rolling humps with steep drops off its edge. The so-called mesa forms something of a rough circle, and the views which that provides are excellent - from the sheer walls of Diablo Canyon, to the Pajarito Canyon and Rio Grande, to the Sangre de Cristos. While this hike is not one referenced in the literature or on-line, it is well worth the trip! '),
('108','Trail399','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'N','Little Tesuque Group','Loop','3.60','600','Moderate','None','Views','All','Mixed sun/shade','Trail399_Clipped.gpx','Trail399_Clipped.json','35.7261020000','-105.8876270000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157679082161630',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.72605,-105.88663/@35.72605,-105.8888187,17z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQzJzMzLjgiTiAxMDXCsDUzJzExLjkiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.72605!4d-105.88663?hl=en',NULL,'Trail 399 starts from the north side of Highway 475 just east of Nun\'s Curve. The route shown in the map is a loop that follows Little Tesuque Creek for a while then goes up and down the foothills. Many options exist along the way, including connections to the Dale Ball trails and the Winsor trail.'),
('109','Galisteo Basin','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','4.70','400','Easy-Moderate','Public Toilet','Mtn Panoramas','Not Summer','Full sun','Galisteo_Basin.GPX','Galisteo_Basin.json','35.4736492900','-105.9265365000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157680990441155','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157679048017501','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Cowboy Shack Trailhead/@35.4800019,-105.9464165,13.35z/data=!4m8!1m2!2m1!1sGalisteo Basin Cowboy Shack!3m4!1s0x8718f99e85a4522b:0x810d7d13b42f8302!8m2!3d35.4730699!4d-105.9269444',NULL,'The Galisteo Basin is a preserve just south of Santa Fe that offers multiple hiking options via numbered trail segments. The area is also well suited for mountain bikes, with relatively easy grades up and down the hills. As you hike any of the sections, the views of the mountains are splendid and in every direction - from the San Pedros, Ortiz, Sandias, Cerrillos Hills and the Sangre de Cristos to the Pecos Region, and Jemez. Even Mount Taylor is visible from the ridge tops. The trails are well-maintained and there are trail maps at many of the segment junctions. The Conservancy group is extending the available trails yearly.'),
('110','Diablo Mesa Loop','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'L','Diablo Canyon Group','Loop','2.50','700','Med-Difficult','None','Cliffs','Not Summer','Full sun','DiabloMesaLoop.gpx','DiabloMesaLoop.json','35.8045013600','-106.1360877000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157680943556556',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Diablo Canyon Recreation Area/@35.8105225,-106.1646954,14.43z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x871841cc309ae52d:0x694906cba94e2b69!8m2!3d35.806363!4d-106.142693','The portion of the actual track up to the mesa top shown in red on the interactive map is steep and difficult - but also very fun. A potentially better route is shown in blue on the proposed map below.','Spectacular views of Diablo Canyon\'s cliffs and surroundings from both in the canyon and from the top of the mesa to the north. Also 360 views that include the Rio Grande and the Jemez and Sangre de Cristo Mountain ranges. '),
('111','La Cieneguilla','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','1.60','40','Easy','None','Petroglyphs','Not Summer','Full sun','Santa_Fe_Petroglyphs.gpx','Santa_Fe_Petroglyphs.json','35.6089500000','-106.1199680000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157681340745155','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157679565341590','https://www.google.com/maps/place/La Cieneguilla Petroglyphs/@35.6034394,-106.1140655,14.12z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87185dd73f6b9be9:0x59a1e66653944280!8m2!3d35.6087644!4d-106.1199676',NULL,'This hike is short but full of pleasant surprises, a popular site for locals. Located not far from Santa Fe, the location is well marked on most maps, and provides an ample parking area along NM56. After a short walk along the fence going south (arrows mark the way), you proceed up into the lava hills through a marked gate. Once near the top, the walk stays high along the mesa and offers some pleasant views of the area - but more amazingly, a large number of petroglyphs. Even compared to the national park system, this area is remarkable for its many close-together carvings and varieties of style - from spirals, to animals, to hands, to odd-shaped characters, including numerous Kokopelli figures. It is a very worthwhile excursion!'),
('112','Embudo Trail','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'O','South Sandia Group','Loop','6.90','1800','Moderate','None','Sandia Views','Not Summer','Full sun','Embudo_Trail.GPX','Embudo_Trail.json','35.0993154200','-106.4805398000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157678122594474','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157678092731623/with/32622096524/','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Embudo Trailhead, Albuquerque, NM 87112/@35.1016622,-106.4980275,14.65z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x8718a1b694ad67ed:0x56ee309f85278023!2sEmbudo Trailhead!8m2!3d35.0991806!4d-106.4802514!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8718a1b694ad67ed:0x56ee309f85278023!2m2!1d-106.4802514!2d35.0991806','About 1.5 miles into the hike and shortly after leaving the neck of the funnel, Embudo Trail takes a left turn up an embankment. See the red flag on the interactive map referenced below. It\'s easy to miss this turn, as the drainage straight ahead also looks like a trail. After a few steps up the embankment, a small sign confirms that you are on Trail 193.','Embudo, a Spanish word for \'funnel\', lives up to its word as the trail winds past the narrow funnel neck and into the bowl\nshaped drainage. The parking area is large, but without facilities. It lies at the east end of Indian School Road, near the south end\nof the Sandias. The lot can get quite crowded on the weekends, as it serves numerous trails in the area. Embudo Trail is identified as Trail 193 and leads directly towards the canyon. It goes just south of a very large tank and north of a large spillway. The trail is quite wide at the beginning but soon narrows as it enters the neck of the funnel. There are numerous\nroutes through the neck, and all require some degree of scrambling, so simply pick one that suits. Once past the neck, the trail resumes as a typical narrow track upwards into the canyon and up to a ridgetop with excellent area views. It is an out-and-back trail and could be extended by following one of the trails that intersects Embudo near its summit.'),
('113','Plaza Blanca','mstr','Abiquiu','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Two-Cars','1.50','180','Easy','None','Sculpted Cliffs','Spring Fall','Full sun','20160730_PlazaBlanca.gpx','20160730_PlazaBlanca.json','36.2323240000','-106.3031640000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157670970815912',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Plaza Blanca/@36.234848,-106.305701,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x83ed79ff2f2c7d9b!8m2!3d36.2326169!4d-106.3026595?hl=en-US','Many options exist for hikers of all levels. But regardless of the route, visitors should be ready to get to high ground in case of a flash flood.','Georgia O\'Keeffe named these landscapes in the Rio Chama Valley near Abiquiu \"The White Place\", or in Spanish \"Plaza Blanca\". Visitors may recognize these sites from O\'Keeffe\'s work or from the many motion pictures which have used them as a backdrop. This area of New Mexico is now on the grounds of the Dar Al Islam education center and mosque. Although this is private land, the center welcomes visitors who wish to hike and view the awe-inspiring landscapes. [Adapted from www.plaza-blanca.com referenced below.]\n<br><br>\nThe Actual Hike Data below is for a relatively short out and back hike with little elevation gain. However, in a few spots you\'ll need to scramble up a short, narrow, steep drainage. The ASCHG Suggested Route under Proposed Hike Data is another alternative. Regardless of the exact route, hikers can choose to explore narrow canyons or climb up to ridge tops for expansive views.\n'),
('114','Little Tesuque Creek','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'N','Little Tesuque Group','Two-Cars','4.40','1000','Moderate','None','Multiple Scenic Vistas','All','Mixed sun/shade','Little_Tesuque.GPX','Little_Tesuque.json','35.7260938500','-105.8864046000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157681800918756','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157681726804875','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.726036,-105.886992/@35.722282,-105.8952134,15.23z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQzJzMzLjciTiAxMDXCsDUzJzEzLjIiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.726036!4d-105.886992',NULL,'This hike interconnects with several other area trails, many of which have differently named segments. The hike taken by the authors actually begins at Little Tesuque Creek and soon traverses north (Juan Trail) to a fence line, at which point the authors proceeded east (Saddleback Trail) and would have eventually connected to the Chamisa Trail, had it been further pursued. It was decided that the Chamisa Trail link would make for a great 2-car hike (stay tuned!). The on-line map reference below gives a nice overview of the area trails. Also, in \"actual data\" below, there is a link to a map showing two other hikes taken by the authors in this area. One of the unique features of this hike was the fact that there were multiple outstanding overlooks providing vistas south and southeast. There was even a man-made stick shelter on one of the bluffs (see photos on full-page map). The hike is well-suited to all seasons as there is ample shade for summer hikes, and the elevation is low enough in the winter to dramatically reduce snow\naccumulations.'),
('115','Diablo South Mesa','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'L','Diablo Canyon Group','Loop','1.80','600','Med-Difficult','None','Cliffs','Not Summer','Mixed sun/shade','DiabloSouthMesa.gpx','DiabloSouthMesa.json','35.8049960000','-106.1400950000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157679869282641',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Diablo Canyon Recreation Area/@35.8105225,-106.1646954,14.43z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x871841cc309ae52d:0x694906cba94e2b69!8m2!3d35.806363!4d-106.142693','Find the path up the south flank of the canyon wall where the track starts on the interactive map or in the GPX file provided below, The first part is not difficult. Some large boulders need scaling further up, and the steep route we took down provides inconsistent footing.','Spectacular views of Diablo Canyon\'s cliffs and surroundings from the top of the mesas that make up the canyon\'s south wall. Also 360 views that include the Rio Grande and the Jemez and Sangre de Cristo Mountain ranges.'),
('116','Armijo-Faulty Trail','mstr','Tijeras','Cluster',NULL,'P','Sulpher Canyon Group','Loop','6.20','800','Easy-Moderate','Picnic Area','Forest Views','Not Winter','Good shade','ArmijoFaulty.GPX','ArmijoFaulty.json','35.1724396500','-106.3764364000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157682544866506',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sandia National Forest Armijo Trail/@35.1658419,-106.3757096,15.59z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x871898406b005d3f:0xce1671de455e547f!8m2!3d35.1622839!4d-106.371206',NULL,'This trail is part of a system of trails embedded on the eastern slopes of the Sandia, many of which are located along NM 536. This particular hike starts near the Sulpher Canyon area, and although the authors went in mid-April, part of the access road was still blocked for the winter. This translates into an additional mile of hiking (out and back) to reach the actual trailhead of the Armijo Trail. The Armijo is relatively easy with gradual elevation change, and very well shaded. At its terminus, the tail intersects the Faulty Trail, which can be taken east to form a loop back to the trailhead of Armijo by following the Cienega Trail when Faulty intersects it. The first part of the Faulty Trail from the intersection with Armijo is somewhat steeper, and prior to its intersection with the Cienega Trail, it offers a lovely vista eastwrd, where the San Pedro Mountains can be glimpsed, along with a lovely wooded canyon. Following the Cienega to its end at a picnic area, the loop is closed by following the road back down to the Armijo trailhead.'),
('117','CDT: Deadman Peaks','mstr','San Luis','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','2.90','250','Easy-Moderate','None','Mesa Edge Views','Not Summer','Full sun','DeadmanPeaks.GPX','DeadmanPeaks.json','35.7433703800','-107.0744680000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683144604796',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.7436111,-107.0744444/@35.7118947,-107.1064558,13.12z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQ0JzM3LjAiTiAxMDfCsDA0JzI4LjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.7436111!4d-107.0744444',NULL,'This portion of the Continental Divide Trail (CDT) starts at its junction with BLM 1102 near San Luis, in Cabezon country. The hike skirts the base of Deadman Peaks, offering lovely views of the valley below and out into the Cabezon Wilderness. The CDT is very well marked with cairns along the way, as well as one marking its departure from the dirt road BLM 1102. Park near the hoodoos just off 1102 where it joins with another two-track dirt road, and walk a short distance north on 1102 to the juncture with the CDT. There are some interesting rock features as well en route, including the turtle-shaped rock shown in one of the hike photos. The round-trip hike departs the CDT near its branch east from its north-bound segment. From there it is a short jaunt west to 1102 and back to the starting point. According to multiple links on the web, there is also a run or foot race held here.'),
('118','Las Huertas de Placitas','mstr','Placitas','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','4.40','350','Easy','None','Panoramic Views','Not Summer','Full sun','Huertas_de_Placitas.GPX','Huertas_de_Placitas.json','35.3397061400','-106.4603452000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157681270182061',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B020\'23.2%22N+106%C2%B027\'37.2%22W/@35.3167208,-106.4834579,13z','There are multiple two-track dirt roads criss-crossing the area, so be careful to have a clear plan with regard to your route. Also, there are occasions when fencing must be crossed. Generally these crossings can be navigated fairly easily and, with one exception, there is no barbed wire in the way. ','This land is part of the Open Space program, and winds gently down into Las Huertas Creek north of Placitas. There are great panoramas all along the way, with 360-degree views of the Sangre de Cristos, the Jemez, the Naciemientos, and the Sandia - with occassional views of White Mesa and Cabezon Peak, as well as some local mesas. The dry bed of Las Huertas Creek offers many interesting varieties of rocks, and the cut banks display alternating layers of cobblestones and packed sand. Most of the hike is easy - only one somewhat steep ascent on the return trip (see elevation chart). The book reference contains some interesting anecdotal history of the troubled area. '),
('119','Perea Nature Trail','mstr','San Ysidro','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','1.00','0','Easy','Non','Area Panoramas','Any','Full sun','PereaNatureTrail.gpx','PereaNatureTrail.json','35.5457914000','-106.7818118000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157679528281453',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Perea Nature Trail/@35.5480547,-106.786828,14.97z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87228efa032a19d7:0xf19a7f22e0a91bdb!8m2!3d35.5457403!4d-106.7817257',NULL,'This hike, just off-road US550 south of San Ysidro, is a pleasant stroll offering views of the surrounding terrain - the Jemez, White Mesa, the Sandia, and the Nacimiento Mountains. The level walk traverses a marshy area and loops to the other side along a wide arroyo covered with, what appears to be, gypsum from White Mesa. As the walk is short without elevation change, it makes for a pleasant diversion when passing through the area.'),
('120','Paliza Canyon Goblins','mstr','San Ysidro','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Two-Cars','4.80','450','Easy-Moderate','None','Hoodoos and Goblins','Any','Mixed sun/shade','Paliza_Goblin_Colony.GPX','Paliza_Goblin_Colony.json','35.7089290600','-106.6274303000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157680666183383',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.708935,-106.627287/@35.7078059,-106.6325148,15.35z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQyJzMyLjIiTiAxMDbCsDM3JzM4LjIiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.708935!4d-106.627287',NULL,'This hike, while relatively easy, has some fascinating features: in particular the hoodoos and goblins. The location is north of the little village of Ponderosa in the Jemez Mountain Region, home of a very good winery (Ponderosa Winery) - a logical stopping place on the return trip. Much of the early hike takes you through some lovely, tall Ponderosa trees at a slow incline up to the hoodoo area. Some climbing into the hills is required to access the unusual geology (note the spikes in the elevation chart!). Note also that on the map link below: \"Proposed + Actual Hike Trails\", the two red triangles mark the beginning and end points of the area in which the goblins are to be found. Continuing to follow the dirt jeep track after the \'hairpin turn\' near the end of the goblin area results in a moderate climb up to a ridge where there are some very nice views of the Ponderosa Valley. Due to it\'s remoteness, at least during the Spring when the authors went, there are few fellow hikers. There is a campground not far from the pullover-parking, which may feed additional activity in the Summer. '),
('121','Eldorado Community Preserve','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','2.50','490','Easy-Moderate','None','Views','Not Summer','Full sun','ElDoradoCP.gpx','ElDoradoCP.json','35.5365220000','-105.8837700000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157681262491952',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.5365,-105.88388/@35.5365,-105.8860687,17z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDMyJzExLjQiTiAxMDXCsDUzJzAyLjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.5365!4d-105.88388?hl=en','The Eldorado Community Preserve is on private property owned by El Dorado at Santa Fe. The sign at the trailhead says \"Guests using the Preserve must be with an Eldorado resident.\".','Well marked trails with beautiful 360 views from the hilltops. Several trailheads provide access to different parts of the preserve. See the first picture for details. This hike starts at Trailhead #1'),
('122','Mano Trail','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'O','South Sandia Group','Loop','5.40','1600','Med-Difficult','None','Views of ABQ','Not Summer','Full sun','TomMano.gpx','TomMano.json','35.0989850000','-106.4803550000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157682282811990','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157681209227143','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Embudo Trailhead/@35.0955284,-106.4975803,14.61z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x8718a1b694ad67ed:0x56ee309f85278023!8m2!3d35.0991806!4d-106.4802514','The trails in this area are often unmarked, or markers have been destroyed over time. It is highly recommended to have a defined route for travel. Often there are criss-crossing trails, or sudden turns on the trail you are following that branch off somewhat unexpectedly. There are also sections of Mano that can be rather steep. ','This hike traverses a section of the South Sandias that is somewhat less frequently used, but not devoid of fellow hikers. It begins by following the same trail section utilized by the Embudo Trail, then branches southward. The trail proceeds slightly uphill following the power lines. All along the way, there are great views of the Albuquerque Valley and points north and south. After scaling a steep section, the trail levels out and affords a quiet \'backwater\' scenic area nestled alongside the mountain. It continues up to a \'saddle\' between foothills where the views can be extended eastward, and parts of I-40 can be seen though the pass. All in all, though sometimes a bit of a workout, the hike is a worthwhile scenic venture into the southern portions of the Sandias. '),
('123','Tramway Old La Luz','mstr','Albuquerque','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','7.10','1850','Moderate','Tram Lift Station','Surrounding Views','Not Summer','Full sun','Tramway_Trail.GPX','Tramway_Trail.json','35.1917850800','-106.4791219000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157681752411544','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157682601449570','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Sandia Peak Tramway/@35.185931,-106.4971755,14.4z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87189e8cfbdf7855:0xdee0b10202a6352b!8m2!3d35.1908284!4d-106.4794004',NULL,'The trail starts right at the top of Albuquerque\'s Tram Lift Station Lower Parking Lot and heads north. The trail winds through the foothills, with some minor ups and downs, to the La Luz Trail. From here, the hiker may return to the start or pick some other options as did the authors. Just prior to the juncture with La Luz, the \'Old La Luz\' trail, infrequently used and much steeper with occasional spots where the purchase becomes narrow (not suited for children or pets), veers upward. This trail can be used to make a loop with the newer La Luz, as the two join about 2 miles up. To form a loop, take either of the two La Luz trails to their meeting point then return down the other leg, taking the Tramway Trail back to the start. Near the point where the trails merge, a side trail heads west along a ridge offering a good view of La Cueva Canyon. While part of the Tramway Trail skirts some developments, the trail is never too close, nor in view of homes for any significant distance.'),
('124','La Cienega Santa Fe','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,'Yellow House Group','Loop','3.40','800','Med-Difficult','None','Area views','Not Summer','Full sun','Cienega_Santa_fe.GPX','Cienega_Santa_fe.json','35.5625915100','-106.1322620000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157682643420791','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157682782079220','https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B033\'45.3%22N+106%C2%B007\'56.1%22W/@35.5605004,-106.1347294,15z','Hiker beware! There are some very steep sections to this hike, and the footing is poor, with loose rock and gravel on the surface. The point of descent to the river does not appear passable until you begin to go down and find a way from the flat-top mesa to the Santa Fe River canyon below - via very steep slopes. The photo of the petroglyph on the geomap marks the point. A good verbal description of this point is provided in the book referenced below. ','This tract of BLM land is accessed directly across from mailbox 42 on the Camino Capilla Vieja (CR54) about 0.4 miles from the intersection with CR548 (Entrada La Cienega). There is room for only two cars, and the access is provided through an opening in the fence. This hike, though relatively short, can be challenging (see tips, above). While the views are nice, they might not be worth the effort for the casual hiker. '),
('125','Black Canyon','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','3.70','500','Med-Difficult','Restrooms','Forest Views','All','Good shade','Black_Canyon.GPX','Black_Canyon.json','35.7280911800','-105.8391695000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157664317884224',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Black Canyon Campground/@35.727845,-105.8417405,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x871851e3b9a3e2e5:0x56e842d1c99fd965!8m2!3d35.7278407!4d-105.8395465?hl=en','The route up to the saddle is relatively relatively easy. In colder months, ice on the western section of the split can make for treacherous footing. From the saddle, hikers will encounter some steep sections with loose footing going up in either direction. Hikers can go left or right up to beautiful views.','Black Canyon Campground is in the Santa Fe National Forest. The hike starts at the trailhead parking area just outside the campground. It proceeds up through the campground, continues up the canyon, splits briefly and comes back together. At this junction, hikers can loop back down to the start or proceed further up to a saddle overlooking the Santa Fe Watershed. At the saddle, the trail splits again. Both the left and right routes lead up steep slopes to beautiful views.'),
('126','Tesuque Creek South Fork','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','2.80','1800','Med-Difficult','None','Creek','Summer','Good shade','TesuqueCreekSouthFork.gpx','TesuqueCreekSouthFork.json','35.7603060000','-105.8116510000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157682273620622',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.760306,-105.811651/@35.760306,-105.813845,17z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQ1JzM3LjEiTiAxMDXCsDQ4JzQxLjkiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.760306!4d-105.811651','The hike up the creek and surrounding canyon is difficult in many spots due to water crossings, steep sections, and loose footing. The trail is also difficult to discern and even non-existent for long streches.','This hike follows a little-known trail up the Tesuque Creek South Fork. Other than the sound and sight of water and the forest setting, the hike doesn\'t offer much more than exercise.'),
('127','Sandia Crest Loop','mstr','Albuquerque','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','4.20','800','Easy-Moderate','Tram & Crest Gift Shop','Views of ABQ','Not Winter','Good shade','CrestSpur.gpx','CrestSpur.json','35.2099021000','-106.4494758000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157682479852684',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Sandia Crest, New Mexico 87008/@35.2103569,-106.4512021,15.14z/data=!4m16!1m7!3m6!1s0x87189ea8e13b50bf:0xa16dea7520b0a8cb!2sSandia Crest!3b1!8m2!3d35.2102777!4d-106.4497222!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x87189ea8e13b50bf:0xa16dea7520b0a8cb!2m2!1d-106.4497222!2d35.2102777',NULL,'This hike can be started from either \'end\': the Upper Sandia Tram Station, or the Crest Gift Shop at the end of NM536. Either way, a nice loop can be made via the Crest Trail (130) between the two, and the Crest Spur Trail and La Luz (upper portion). While there are some steep slopes, none of the trail segments are precarious. Early summer offers a wealth of wildflowers to grace the way. One word of caution on the Crest Trail - when coming from the Tram Station, sometimes the trail overlaps with other trails, and the signage is not always clear. '),
('128','Santa Fe Baldy','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'F','Santa Fe Ski Area Group','Loop','14.50','2500','Difficult','Restrooms','Vistas','Summer','Mixed sun/shade','SFBaldyFullLoop.gpx','SFBaldyFullLoop.json','35.7958464000','-105.8043320000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157682677610364',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Winsor Trailhead/@35.7918157,-105.8110332,15z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87184cbfcc11af63:0x1526b1395abfefd!8m2!3d35.7956032!4d-105.8047946','Warning - we have not done this loop yet. It\'s a long hike with two serious up and down sections.','Santa Fe Baldy loop hike with optional stops or turnaround points along the way. '),
('129','Little Tesuque Falls','mstr','Santa Fe','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','2.00','480','Easy-Moderate','None','Falls','All','Mixed sun/shade','LittleTesuqueFalls.gpx','LittleTesuqueFalls.json','35.7458630000','-105.8341230000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157682022052714',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B044\'46.3%22N+105%C2%B050\'03.4%22W/@35.7461916,-105.8366957,15z','Find the trailhead just across the road from the Borrego Bear Wallow parking lot. The trail is hard to follow in spots.','A hard-to-find falls on the upper portion of Little Tesuque Creek. There are a few nice views on the way, but note that so far the authors have not actually seen the falls. The waypoint on the maps shows the falls purported location.'),
('130','Lake Peak','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'F','Santa Fe Ski Area Group','Out-and-back','5.00','2100','Med-Difficult','Restrooms','Craggy Peaks','Summer','Mixed sun/shade','LakePeakSnipped.gpx','LakePeakSnipped.json','35.7955390000','-105.8021660000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157686011303755',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Ski Santa Fe/@35.7131919,-105.804486,12z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x3d71feb58b512092!8m2!3d35.7962521!4d-105.8023739?hl=en','Steep hike up and down via the ski area. Many variations possible up to Deception Peak. Some boulder scrambling required to get to Lake Peak from Deception Peak.','Beautiful 360 views from the tops of Deception Peak and the craggy ridges and summit of Lake Peak. Wildflowers and lichen add color to the already beautiful rock.'),
('131','Tree Spring Crest Trail','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'Q','Tree Spring Group',NULL,'7.70','2000','Moderate','Public Toilet','Sandia Crest Views','Not Winter','Good shade','Tree_Spring.GPX','Tree_Spring.json','35.1940876700','-106.4048437000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683024473172','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157682861696874','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Tree Springs Trailhead/@35.1824029,-106.3978272,13.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87189911fe481135:0x3847221ed2c4ad71!8m2!3d35.193298!4d-106.40535',NULL,'This is a somewhat popular trail in the Sandias, accessible from the Sandia Crest Road (536) on the east side of the mountain. It not only provides good shade, a variety of wildflowers, and views, but also has a relatively mild inclination. At the end of the trail, it intersects the Crest Trail, which formed a part of this hike. The Tree Spring portion is only about 2 miles each way, and so offers accessibility to casual hikers. Also at its terminus is a pleasant open space overlooking the valley. Continuing north about 1-3/4 miles from the intersection with the Crest Trail, you will reach the Sandia Tram, and all of its accompanying spectacular views. '),
('132','Puerto Nambe','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'F','Santa Fe Ski Area Group','Out-and-back','9.20','2500','Moderate','Restrooms','Mtn Views','Summer','Mixed sun/shade','Puerto_Nambe.GPX','Puerto_Nambe.json','35.7954792500','-105.8042622000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157686195902145','https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683783904981','https://www.google.com/maps/place/Winsor Trailhead/@35.7918157,-105.8110332,15z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87184cbfcc11af63:0x1526b1395abfefd!8m2!3d35.7956032!4d-105.8047946','Hike is relatively long but otherwise not difficult. Use gpx or signs to know which way to turn at key junctions.','Great hike for mountain views, cascading creeks, wildflowers, mountain meadows. Turnaround point is just past the junction for making the ascent to Santa Fe Baldy. Other extension options include Lake Katherine, Stewart Lake, and a more difficult loop back via Lake Peak.'),
('133','Sandia Cave','mstr','Placitas','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','1.20','150','Easy','None','Cave and Views','Not Winter','Full sun','Sandia_Cave.GPX','Sandia_Cave.json','35.2501605079','-106.4101114030',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683357066722',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Sandia Man Cave, Placitas, NM 87043/@35.2712173,-106.4466139,13.09z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x87189ba59d32c875:0x80265dcf8bdb5b41!2sSandia Man Cave!8m2!3d35.2550155!4d-106.405993!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x87189ba59d32c875:0x80265dcf8bdb5b41!2m2!1d-106.405993!2d35.2550155','The last 2.5 miles of the road to the cave is poorly maintained and can be deeply rutted in places. A high clearance vehicle is strongly recommended.','The cave hike is an easy family-level hike for all ages, and the area view are quite rewarding. The trail ascends gradually, offering views of the north Sandias along the way. The cave itself is accessed by a sturdy steel spiral staircase, and the first few feet of the cave have adequate clearance for viewing inside. Views from the cave are also quite good. It is a relatively popular place, even though road access is marginal. The site is well marked on the road.'),
('134','Piedra Lisa - La Luz Link','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'K','Piedra Lisa Group','Out-and-back','1.30','300','Easy','None','Sandia Views','All','Full sun','PiedraLisa-LaLuzLink.GPX','PiedraLisa-LaLuzLink.json','35.2228694502','-106.4834139120',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157684842729330',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Piedra Lisa-south Trailhead, State Rte 333 D, Sandia Pueblo, NM 87004/@35.2119487,-106.5021179,14.04z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x87189c33b662307d:0x92c0ead8cf18c3c4!2sPiedra Lisa-south Trailhead!8m2!3d35.2231347!4d-106.4834646!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x87189c33b662307d:0x92c0ead8cf18c3c4!2m2!1d-106.4834646!2d35.2231347',NULL,'This short link trail has some ups and downs, but is relatively easy and offers some unique views of the Sandias. It is well marked from the Piedra Lisa end, but not from La Luz. If beginning from La Luz, take the trail immediately to the left after climbing the steps up from the parking lot. Be careful - once the trail gets going, there are numerous other dead end trails that make identification of the link trail a bit tricky. The author ended up in a small box canyon on one such trail. Not many hikers take this trail, so it is good in general for solitary hiking.               '),
('135','Travertine Falls','mstr','Tijeras','Cluster',NULL,'R','South Crest Group','Out-and-back','1.50','350','Easy','None','Travertine Caves and Falls','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','Travertine_Falls.GPX','Travertine_Falls.json','35.0894528534','-106.3914393730',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683838569732',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Travertine Falls, Grand Enchantment Trail, Cedar Crest, NM 87008/@35.0878409,-106.399459,15.39z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x8718a25563f2e5d7:0xf849c028caed8b2a!2sTravertine Falls!8m2!3d35.0951739!4d-106.393809!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8718a25563f2e5d7:0xf849c028caed8b2a!2m2!1d-106.393809!2d35.0951739',NULL,'NOTE: The track indicated on the map actually extends beyond the falls area, as the author wished to explore a bit of the South Crest Trail. The Travertine Falls area is a rather popular short and easy hike suitable for a family outing. The trail ascends gradually to the falls area, but at times, the waterflow can be low. The travertine caves, formed by the falls, are nonetheless worth seeing. The trail is the initial part of the Sandia South Crest Trail, which ascends to the crest and proceeds almost 26 miles to Placitas. While there are not a lot of views en route, the hike makes for a pleasant and enjoyable outing.'),
('136','Guaje Canyon','mstr','Los Alamos','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7.50','1650','Moderate','None','Canyon views','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','GuajeCanyon.gpx','GuajeCanyon.json','35.8957770000','-106.3920720000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157684309181452','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157687700914535','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Pajarito Mountain Ski Area, 397 Camp May Rd, Los Alamos, NM 87544/@35.8871552,-106.3942851,13.76z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x87180dcc3daf4c17:0x56606c59df7070e7!2sPajarito Mountain Ski Area!8m2!3d35.8950144!4d-106.3909148!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x87180dcc3daf4c17:0x56606c59df7070e7!2m2!1d-106.3909148!2d35.8950144',NULL,'This hike takes one through a lot of new growth - shrubs, young Aspens, and tons of wildflowers - a resurgence after the Los Alamos fire in 2011. Most of the elevation change is easy with the exception traversing Pipeline Road to the overlook area, which is steep though not long. Because of the open areas from the burn, and some large meadows, wildflowers proliferate. There are several areas where the forest remains intact, the fire having missed. The views into the Valles Caldera, and at the Guaje Canyon Overlook, as well as along the ridge leading up to the overlook, are quite striking and well worth the hike. Parking is located at the west end of the Pajarito Ski Area Parking Lot - the trail begins on the right, shortly up the dirt road extension from the lot.'),
('137','La Cienega - Sandia','mstr','Tijeras','Cluster',NULL,'P','Sulpher Canyon Group','Out-and-back','4.90','1750','Med-Difficult','Picnic Area','Views from Sandia Crest','Not Winter','Good shade','SandiaCienega.gpx','SandiaCienega.json','35.1697340000','-106.3842440000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157684595293741','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157684165970363','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Cienega Picnic Area, Highway 536, Sandia Park, NM 87059/@35.1670433,-106.3806846,14.24z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x871898507899712d:0x9167b4084fd81884!2sCienega Picnic Area!8m2!3d35.1691362!4d-106.382774!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x871898507899712d:0x9167b4084fd81884!2m2!1d-106.382774!2d35.1691362',NULL,'This hike is more challenging than the distance to the top would imply - the trail is somewhat overgrown (summer), relentlessly ascends, and at times is rutted and difficult to secure proper footing. It traverses the east side of the Sandia, and does not provide much in the way of scenic opportunities along the way. When it finally reaches the Sandia Crest Trail, it does so in a saddle, joining the Pino Trail from the west. If the hiker is not armed with the knowledge of the great viewpoint a few hundred feet from the juncture with the Crest Trail (as provided by the source below: Sandia Mountain Hiking Guide), the trip would have ended up nothing more than great exercise. The views there were excellent.'),
('138','Mora Flats','mstr','Pecos','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','7.70','1000','Easy-Moderate','Campground','Ridgeline Views','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','Mora_Flats.GPX','Mora_Flats.json','35.8405867964','-105.6202201270',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157684705881921','https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157684906090203','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Iron Gate Campground, Rociada, NM 87742/@35.8201393,-105.6603879,13.88z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x8719b73523d278c3:0x96f360002b26a4b7!2sIron Gate Campground!8m2!3d35.8399489!4d-105.6203145!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8719b73523d278c3:0x96f360002b26a4b7!2m2!1d-105.6203145!2d35.8399489','From NM63, the road splits south of Cowles. The road leading to the Iron Gate Campground and trailheads may have some challenging sections - steep, rutted or water-logged. Use an appropriate vehicle.','This trail is not difficult, and soon approaches a ridge offering great views of the valley to the East. Wildflowers adorn the path. Eventually, the trail descends at a reasonable rate to the meadow at Mora Flats, and to the banks of the Mora River. Due to its somewhat remote location, this hike offers solitude as well as pleasant scenery.   '),
('139','Pecos Trail 271','mstr','Pecos','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','7.00','1800','Easy-Moderate','Campgrounds/Picnic Area','Mountain Views','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','CowlesTrail271.gpx','CowlesTrail271.json','35.8123370000','-105.6592860000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157683023757112','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157685810565366','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Cowles Ponds Fishing Site (recgovnpsdata), Tererro, NM 87573/@35.8112212,-105.6673849,15.55z/data=!4m15!1m6!3m5!1s0x8719b115f217cd91:0x77179e63ec74df90!2sCowles Ponds Fishing Site (recgovnpsdata)!8m2!3d35.8116566!4d-105.6600047!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8719b115f217cd91:0x77179e63ec74df90!2m2!1d-105.6600047!2d35.8116566',NULL,'This hike begins almost at the end of NM63 North from Pecos. This trailhead is the site of multiple hiking possibilities, one of which is Trail 271, the subject of this hike. This hike, if extended far enough, becomes the Stewart Lake hike, making for a 10.8 mile out-and-back. Without going to Stewart Lake however, views of the valley and of the Sangre de Cristo range are well worth the shorter hike. This is not a highly trafficked area, so there is also plenty of solitude, lots of wildflowers, and thick groves of Aspens. The elevation change is gradual and not difficult.'),
('140','Serpent Lake','mstr','Taos','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'6.75','1690','Med-Difficult','Parking only','Mountain Lake','Summer','Mixed sun/shade','SerpentLake.gpx','SerpentLake.json','36.0576980000','-105.5006400000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157685838330940',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//36.05766,-105.50064/@35.9604486,-105.5804196,11z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzbCsDAzJzI3LjYiTiAxMDXCsDMwJzAyLjMiVw!3b1!8m2!3d36.05766!4d-105.50064?hl=en','Four mile dirt road to trailhead is dusty and has a few ruts. Otherwise not a difficult drive. ','Nice hike up through the woods and ultimately to Serpent Lake with beautiful views of the surrounding ridge. Wildflowers and grasses provide color.'),
('141','Oso Corredor Connector','mstr','Tijeras','Cluster',NULL,'Q','Tree Spring Group',NULL,'7.70','1000','Easy-Moderate','Public Toilet','Views and Wildflowers','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','Oso_Corredor.GPX','Oso_Corredor.json','35.1931196451','-106.4031978420',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157686459213233',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Tree Springs Trailhead/@35.1839513,-106.4130963,13.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87189911fe481135:0x3847221ed2c4ad71!8m2!3d35.193298!4d-106.40535','Check the Sandia Ranger Station or facebook for latest info on trail closings. In late August/early September, sections can be closed off due to a feeding bear population, and from winter on, until the snow melts sometime in the Spring.     ','This trail can only be reached from another trail - either Tree Spring (in this case), or Faulty Trail (Doc Long Picnic Area). From Tree Spring, it is a short walk up to the juncture with Oso Corredor, and well-marked. Immediately, the hiker is struck with bursts of color in mini-meadows along a well-maintained, gently sloping trail. It seems not many hikers take this route, so there is a fair amount of solitude and quiet. There are also occasional views of the interior portion of the Sandias. The grade is gentle and you barely notice it while walking along this lovely trail. This particular hike proceeded past the intersection with Faulty for additional viewing and enjoyment.'),
('142','Crest - Faulty Loop','mstr','Tijeras','Cluster',NULL,'R','South Crest Group','Loop','5.80','1200','Moderate','None','Occasional views','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','Crest-Faulty_Loop.GPX','Crest-Faulty_Loop.json','35.0895033963','-106.3914033300',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157688970549785',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Arrowhead Trail, Tijeras, NM 87059/@35.0854971,-106.3963912,15.16z/data=!4m16!1m7!3m6!1s0x8718a300d1e0078f:0xd327add59d6d8629!2sArrowhead Trail, Tijeras, NM 87059!3b1!8m2!3d35.0888891!4d-106.3913648!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x8718a300d1e0078f:0xd327add59d6d8629!2m2!1d-106.3913648!2d35.0888891',NULL,'This hike begins at the south terminus of the Sandia Crest Trail, and features a trickle-waterfall (Travertine Falls) as well as the beginning of the Faulty Trail extending 8.6 miles north. As the Faulty Trail heads uphill - steep for a short distance, then continually less grade - it meets the north end of a short connecting segment, the Upper Faulty Trail. During this part of the trip, there are not a lot of views, as the tree cover is extensive. A sharp turn left along Upper Faulty Trail takes the hiker on fairly level ground to the juncture with Trail 130 - the Crest Trail. Following that trail downhill returns you to the trailhead. One feature of this loop is that there are some breaks allowing views from southwest to the Manzano Mountains, to northeast to the San Pedro Mountains. It is also not heavily traveled (after Travertine Falls) and allows some solitude and quiet in the woods.             '),
('143','Fletcher Trail','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'K','Piedra Lisa Group','Out-and-back','4.50','1100','Moderate','None','Sandia Views','All','Mixed sun/shade','Fletcher_Trail.GPX','Fletcher_Trail.json','35.2229277883','-106.4834435000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157685825508012',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/Piedra Lisa-south Trailhead/@35.2092174,-106.5091207,14.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x87189c33b662307d:0x92c0ead8cf18c3c4!8m2!3d35.2231347!4d-106.4834646','Although this hike is rated \"Moderate\", much of the trail is easy, but there is one stretch where the slope is steep and the footing is somewhat loose. The author traversed this section two days after some good rain, and the soil was more compact, but drier conditions could present some difficulty. Note: The trail is closed between March 1 and August 15.    ','This relatively short trail is accessed from the Piedra Lisa Trail, about 0.8 miles in where the trail dips down into a shallow gulley, the meeting place of a couple of arroyos. Piedra Lisa continues to the left, and Fletcher branches off to the right, soon heading east towards the Sandia\'s Shield. The views offered by Fletcher Trail are very nice, and the trail ends up approaching \"The Prow\", a prominent feature viewable at this end of the Sandias. Except for the steep section, the trail is pleasant as it follows the arroyo upstream. There are multiple views of the mountains en route.      '),
('144','Diablo West Mesa','mstr','Santa Fe','Cluster',NULL,'L','Diablo Canyon Group','Loop','2.50','500','Med-Difficult','None','Views','Not Summer','Full sun','DiabloWestMesa.gpx','DiabloWestMesa.json','35.8142830000','-106.1500790000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157687758648164',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/place/35%C2%B048\'52.0%22N+106%C2%B008\'59.9%22W/@35.7899439,-106.1561384,12z?authuser=0&hl=en-US','\n    The parking spot shown shortens the walk to the start of the trail up the mesa. An alternative is to park in the Diablo Canyon lot and enjoy the slightly longer hike through Diablo Canyon itself. Regardless, use the map and gpx file and follow the cairns to find your way up to the mesa top. Some scrambling is required. Then loop south across the mesa for a somewhat challenging descent down a side canyon. The first part of the descent requires about 20 feet of climbing down a sort of rock ladder. After that it\'s mainly scrambling down bolders and avoiding any muddy spots. Note that either the up or down route could be used to close the loop on the Sagebrush Flats hike (see reference below).\n    ','Spectacular views of Diablo Canyon\'s cliffs and surroundings from the top of the mesas that make up the canyon\'s west wall. Also 360 views that include the Rio Grande and the Jemez and Sangre de Cristo Mountain ranges. Part of the route up follows what seems to be an old wagon road. See the Old Gate picture below.\n    '),
('145','Ball Ranch','mstr','Golden','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Loop','5.50','650','Easy-Moderate','None','Colored Hills','Not Summer','Full sun','Ball_Ranch.GPX','Ball_Ranch.json','35.3898331895','-106.3032204290',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157661679047818','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157661591623668','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.3916667,-106.27/@35.4327041,-106.3364561,12.84z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDIzJzMwLjAiTiAxMDbCsDE2JzEyLjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.3916667!4d-106.27','Entrance to the Trailhead is off of 57A, a gravel road, at a BLM gate which requires a key. The key can be obtained without charge at a BLM office. Once past the gate, the road becomes very difficult and requires a 4-wheel drive with reasonable clearance. The branch off of this road to the windmill at the trailhead may not be traversable, depending on recent weather conditions, but is only about 1/4 mile away and can be easily walked (as the authors did in this case). When following the arroyo, near the canyon\' end is a point of departure which is not obvious. Refer to the marked location on the map. ','This loop hike begins in the arroyo near the windmill (see book reference, below), and immediately enters a shallow canyon. The canyon walls vary as the hike progresses, and there are many interesting geological features along the way, accented by many color changes and rock sizes. Once the trail departs from the arroyo, the views increase as multi-colored hills become visible. Also, a short distance from the arroyo is an area containing large petrified tree trunk pieces. Petrified wood is scattered along the trail from here. Overall, the trail presents many great views and interesting features.'),
('146','Boundary Loop Trail','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'S','La Cueva Road Group','Loop','3.80','1000','Moderate','None','Interior Rincon and Sandias','Not Summer','Full sun','Boundary_Loop.GPX','Boundary_Loop.json','35.2024943009','-106.5043653175',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157689963292856',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.20265,-106.5038833/@35.2019097,-106.5085099,15.87z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDEyJzA5LjUiTiAxMDbCsDMwJzE0LjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.20265!4d-106.5038833',NULL,'This hike starts across the road from a broad dirt parking area on FR333 just north of the turn-off from Tramway Blvd. The most difficult part is the very beginning - a steep but short stretch to the top of the nearby ridge. After that the trail follows a contour so attentive footing is required for a short distance - not a sheer drop but a rather steep angle. Most of the hike is an easy walk up the arroyo if you take the suggested path and follow the east branch of the loop up. A 5 ft rock wall must be scaled, but it is rather easy to do so with multiple foot- and hand-holds. From here, the views are spectacular. Great interior views of the Rincon Ridge, and some lovely angles on the Sandias. At the northern end, the trail is elevated to the point that a nice vista of Juan Tabo Canyon presents itself (see the Juan Tabo Canyon Hike). Multiple trails crisscross the area providing more great views. The author traversed a couple of these which made the nominal 2.5 mile hike a bit longer.                '),
('147','Juan Tabo Cabin','mstr','Albuquerque','Cluster',NULL,'S','La Cueva Road Group','Out-and-back','1.00','500','Easy','None','Sandia and Valley Views','Not Summer','Full sun','Juan_Tabo_Cabin.gpx','Juan_Tabo_Cabin.json','35.2026998000','-106.5038574000',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157690676899476',NULL,'https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.20265,-106.5038833/@35.1981903,-106.5097481,14.8z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDEyJzA5LjUiTiAxMDbCsDMwJzE0LjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.20265!4d-106.5038833',NULL,'Although this hike is an easy stroll up an arroyo to the old CCC Headquarters ruins, don\'t mistake that for uninteresting! There are multiple wonderful views of the Sandias, and of the valley on the return trip of this out-and-back hike. The cabin itself can actually be seen from the nearby road, FR333 - which leads to the Juan Tabo Picnic Grounds and La Luz Trailhead. The cabin is surrounded by a low stone wall, and a low point in that wall allows close-up access to the interior of the cabin, revealing its architecture. The parking area is shortly after FR333 turns north from Tramway Blvd, and just past the second cattle guard. '),
('148','Stable Mesa','mstr','Jemez Springs','Normal',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Out-and-back','4.20','950','Moderate','None','Jemez Mtns and Valley','Not Winter','Mixed sun/shade','Stable_Edited.GPX','Stable_Edited.json','35.7917451952','-106.7753870320',NULL,NULL,'https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157665831300339','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/sets/72157688924451021/with/24692491998/','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.8183333,-106.7880556/@35.7999943,-106.8429912,12.03z/data=!4m8!1m7!3m6!1s0x0:0x0!2zMzXCsDQ5JzA2LjAiTiAxMDbCsDQ3JzE3LjAiVw!3b1!8m2!3d35.8183333!4d-106.7880556',NULL,'This hike takes you deep into the Jemez territory about 7 miles up FR376, past Gilman Tunnels where the road turns into fairly well-maintained gravel. The starting point begins across the road from the pull-off, which is on the west side of 376 near a bridge over the Guadalupe River. Walking just past the bridge, on the right, the trail starts. The trail begins with a pleasant walk alongside the river and then moves into Ponderosa forest before heading up the mesa. The trail up is somewhat steep and the  gravel is a bit loose, prompting the authors to rename the hike \"Unstable Mesa\". Once on top of the mesa, the views get quite interesting. There are multiple fascinating rock formations along the mesa\'s edge, many with erosion-built holes. From there, a loop can be made back to the point of first ascension. There are remains of a logging camp and pueblo ruins, but the authors did not locate them on this journey. Refer to the referenced book for more details.'),
('149','Canada de la Cueva    ','mstr','Cerrillos','Normal','','','','Out-and-back','7.80','450','Easy-Moderate','None    ','Geology in Arroyo    ','Not Summer  ','Full sun','Canada_de_la_Cueva.GPX','Canada_de_la_Cueva.json','35.4386154469','-106.0184755269','','','https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157689658210665','https://www.flickr.com/photos/30474783@N06/albums/72157689909068565','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//35.4386549,-106.0184904/@35.5076537,-106.12594,10.88z/data=!4m2!4m1!3e0','','This hike had no siginificant elevation changes, and simply followed the arroyo into the Galisteo Basin. Near the end of the hike the land turns into privately held land, but there are no warning signs indicating same. One source showed the hike as a two-car hike, but would require utilizing the private land to accomplish. The arroyo seemed to hold an unending variety of interesting geology - from rocks of all colors and shapes to hills and embankments of varying composition. According to the reference below, it also is the home of a considerable variety of wildlife, but at the time the authors  explored the area, little was to be seen. The hike may be shortened and still provide a fascinating look at the Galisteo basin.'),
('150','Bosque River Loop','mstr','Albuquerque','At VC','99','','','Loop','2.10','50','Easy','Rio Grande Nature Center','Bosque and River Views','Any','Mixed sun/shade','Bosque-River-Loop.GPX','Bosque-River-Loop.json','35.1306509972','-106.6844876390','','','https://www.flickr.com/photos/139088815@N08/albums/72157679147304911','','https://www.google.com/maps/dir//Rio+Grande+Nature+Center,+2901+Candelaria+Rd+NW,+Albuquerque,+NM+87107/@35.1283996,-106.6895061,15.09z/data=!4m8!4m7!1m0!1m5!1m1!1s0x872272fb9f976ba3:0xfbb3b856575dcf74!2m2!1d-106.6828715!2d35.1286772','','This is an easy and pleasant stroll through the Bosque at the Rio Grande Nature Center. There is no elevation change to speak of, and there are meandering cross-trails to explore if you are interested. There is a variety of bird life at all times of the year, along with some explanatory signs that highlight the history of the area. One such historical reference explains the \'Jetty Jacks \'visible along segments of the trail. In addition to weaving through stands of old Cottonwoods and Russian Olive trees, the hike also brings you to the edge of the Rio Grande thereby presenting yet another picturesque aspect to the hike. There are numerous wildflowers in the summer season.');
